Text.Value: Wait.
Come - now is not the time for a crisis of faith. Go on. Kill me. You won't be the first.

EditorData.NodeContext: Like a parent chastising a naughty child.

Text.Value: Release me. I beg you.
I'm sure you've met my mother. You've seen her pale face in the night sky - Sel√ªne, the Moonmaiden.
No - you'll stay where you are.
Know I will feel every wound, and still I will hurt less than you, who so utterly yourself defile.
How many of your Dark Justiciar brethren have run my heart through? How many times have I, immortal, risen again, to await the next?
I never forget a face.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Stock still. Cold. Staring the player dead in the eyes.
EditorData.NodeContext: With a deep, seething foreboding
EditorData.SFXTags: hands disapears as Nightsong goes back to her allowed place
EditorData.VFXTags: hands disapears as Nightsong goes back to her allowed place

Text.Value: I'm here to help you - not harm you.
That and nothing more. So certain was Balthazar that I had no friends in this place. Oh, how he taunted and cajoled.
Your eyes are keen. Free me. You will enjoy what comes next.
A Sharran with a heart? No... perhaps you are no Sharran at all.
Some would call his experiments heretical - I simply thought them cruel. Unnecessary.
A valiant performance. I admit, my heart lit like a full moon when you struck down that cadaver.

EditorData.stateContext:
Nightsong has been 'killed' by the player; she has resurrected now.
 She'll start off injured and slowly recover with each subsequent node.

Text.Value: To think I nearly thought my anguish done. To think I nigh believed you weren't one of Shar's footmen.
How are you the source of Ketheric's invulnerability?
*The Spear of Night could be meant to sacrifice the Nightsong - but are you the one supposed to wield it?*

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Player produces the spear of night and looks at it.

Text.Value: That is when this immortal will visit you, Sharran. That is when I will show you what it is to be afraid.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: She steps forward in anger; on 'What it is to be afraid' she overdoes it and the hands appear again, seizing her and pulling her back. They fade as her line fades and she steps back into place.
EditorData.NodeContext: Fully recovered now.
EditorData.SFXTags: glowing sound on the hands that keep Nightsong captive
EditorData.VFXTags: glowing on the hands that keep Nightsong captive

Text.Value: I thought the 'Nightsong' was some relic. When I realised you were a person, I couldn't justify helping Balthazar.
I showed you my heart; now use your head, young warrior. How will you fly this place without my helping hand?
Do as she says: kill her.
I cannot prevent you. But I can advise you. Be careful to whom you yoke your fate.

EditorData.NodeContext: Spelling it out for the player- hell no.

Text.Value: To eat his sins. Shall I take yours too?

EditorData.NodeContext: With a steely edge, bracing herself for what she believes is coming - the sword through her heart.

Text.Value: What will happen when I do?
A century have I been subject to endless death - at hands so like your own.
Leave.
Balthazar didn't send me here - I came of my own accord.
And I have naught but time.
You, who seek to claim the ultimate prize.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: She looks up and sneers, gesticulating powerfully with her arms

Text.Value: You say you're immortal - how is that so?
Attack.
I accept my fate - for now. But the life of a divine is longer than you can fathom, Sharran. And this cold chapter will close, one day.
Then your task is done. Lay a hand upon me in camaraderie, and I will be free.
I am no Sharran. I've come to free you.
I am no Sharran.
A maxim simple and noble - too noble for a Sharran. Perhaps I named you false.
Even one who had crossed a terrible threshold just prior; even one who had driven me to death.

EditorData.NodeContext: Referencing the fact that the player killed her.

Text.Value: Shar herself could not dim her face. And you will never dim mine.
Shar kept you ignorant, did she? Or was it Ketheric? Perhaps they forgot to tell you they'd make a murderer of you yet.

EditorData.NodeContext: A mirthless humor in her voice

Text.Value: I am Dame Aylin. Out of this hellish realm I carry my sword by the blessing of my mother, Sel√ªne.
Why do you call me Sharran?
And your purpose?
Keep it, if you wish. It is nothing but a bauble now. Just free me.
Leave her.
But perhaps... an inoculation, to make the sickness less catching. If you seek to harm Ketheric, our aims are aligned. If you seek to make him vulnerable, your task is done.
I'm [GEN_PlayerName_c11eee1e-7815-6143-7233-f2427799fa53]. I need to kill Ketheric Thorm.
Leave her.
An intriguing fray. You lay low the Dark Lady's messenger - your ally, your friend. Perhaps you wish to slay the 'Nightsong' yourself, Sharran.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: This greeting if the player rejected SH's COM moment and ultimately killed her.

Text.Value: How much is your freedom worth to you?
I'm someone who can recognise a good opportunity.
I have questions for you, first.
Good. Foolish prey makes for easy finding.

EditorData.NodeContext: She grimaces at you, then snorts a huge loogie and spits it on the ground, then turns away.

Text.Value: This cursed place is far from our Lady's favour - why would you walk here?
No. Please.

EditorData.NodeContext: Bravado melts for a moment. She really is desperate to get out of here, and oyu are her best bet.

Text.Value: And I? I will come for you. When the time is right. When your sons are grown and your beard is long and wiry; when you cannot hold your nightly water and your nose grows as long as your weary, weary days...

And I? I will come for you. When the time is right. When your daughters are grown and your chin sprouts whiskers dark - when your teeth are yellow as corn and your sleep grows short and your days are long and weary, so weary...
And I? I will come for you. When the time is right. When your children are grown and your eyes are weak; when your nose grows as long as your weary, weary days...

EditorData.NodeContext: A cold threat. Not yet at full strength, but you wouldn't tell by her tone.

Text.Value: It would be a delight to grant your desired death, my lady.
Say more. Please.

EditorData.NodeContext: Dubious but wants to hear more, afraid to believe you're really going to help

Text.Value: Free me, and I will forgive your transgressions - generous, don't you think?
I'm ready to fly this place. Are you?
I have all the time in the world. How about you?

EditorData.NodeContext: Needling the player.

Text.Value: But why betray your kinsman? Why turn your ire on he who sent you here? Go on, Sharran - speak.

EditorData.NodeContext: Trying to figure the player out. A hint of hope in her voice, but with an edge - she does not trust easily.

Text.Value: Perhaps I can still kill you - I found a spear that seems intended for that very purpose.
You will have done what your Dark Lady requires - you will have slain a child of Sel√ªne. You will be a Dark Justiciar. Isn't it so?
Ha! A century have I been confined here - and I would spend a century more in devoted gratitude to they who set me free.
Present your weapon, soldier. Plunge it into the Nightsong. I cannot stop you. But know this:

EditorData.AnimationTags: [REUSE] NS: Turns defiantly towards the Speaker, enter standard staging.
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: On "Present your weapon, soldier," She abruptly turns to the player and points an accusing finger. As she moves and points she steps forward. Magical hands appear around her wrists, arms, and shoulders, showing the player how she is bound. If she moves too far, she'll be pulled back by her arms. She looks down at the hands and grimaces in rage, stepping back into place as the hands fade: "Plunge it into the Nightsong. I cannot stop you. But know this. Slams chest again, fury in her movements.

EditorData.VFXTags: glowing on the hands that keep Nightsong captive

Text.Value: Is that all it takes?
A century I have known naught but sorrow; rage. A century have I been Ketheric's captive.
Congratulations - your mistress Shar will write your name on her hand.

EditorData.NodeContext: Bitter sarcasm in her voice. She thinks the player is the lowest of the low - a violent idiot. Injured, but regaining strength.

Text.Value: Kill you? I found a spear that seems intended for that very purpose.
I'm no Sharran. I'm something far worse.
I must decide what to do with you.
This cage links us, like a parasite's fangs to its host. I am immortal; while I am trapped here, so is he.
And I - hah - I will die. Then live. And when the next of your ilk comes with sword aloft or arrow nocked, I'll die again.
Go on. Lay a hand upon my shoulder, and I shall be free.
HAH! By all means, Sharran. Decide.

EditorData.NodeContext: Haughty. She may be trapped, but she in no way feels her fate is in the player's hands.

Text.Value: A hundred years. More, perhaps. Concocted by Ketheric, enacted by Balthazar, my misery has been my centuries' long companion.
What happens if I do as you say - plunge my weapon into your heart?
You're the Nightsong. A person. Not a relic.
Open this cage.
Free her from her bonds.
Run your coop all you like, chicken. You cannot fly without my wings.
Do I name you false?
Perhaps I shouldn't...
I will kill you for pleasure, not Lady Shar.
I was really looking forward to using this spear, though.
Maybe it would be safer to just kill you. I found a spear in this place that seems perfect for the task.
Then lay a hand upon my shoulder, and I shall be free.
I get a bit obsessive about murder at times, but I'm no cultist! That's just rude.
Run along now. Go tell your darling master Ketheric what a good girl you've been.
Run along now. Go tell your darling master Ketheric what a good boy you've been.
Run along now. Go tell your darling master Ketheric what a good child you've been.

EditorData.NodeContext: With aggression re: Ketheric. It's clear she's invting Ketheric down here so she can destroy him.

Text.Value: I am not one of Shar's servants.
Come for more blood, you dog?

EditorData.NodeContext: Complete bitterness; the player has killed her once already

Text.Value: Usually there is a lot more struggling and screaming when I'm about to kill someone.

How many times have you given that speech?
A promise - the most sacred I can give. Release me and I will kill Ketheric Thorm.
Free me, and Ketheric will bleed.
Do as she asks.
Do what you came to do, Sharran. Then run to your darling master Ketheric and tell him what a good girl you've been.
Do what you came to do, Sharran. Then run to your darling master Ketheric and tell him what a good boy you've been.
Do what you came to do, Sharran. Then run to your darling master Ketheric and tell him what a good child you've been.

Text.Value: I'm a friend. Let me free you.
I didn't realise you were a person - not a relic. Let's get you out of here.
No? Then correct me. By all means, little warrior, explain yourself.

EditorData.NodeContext: A demand, not a question.

Text.Value: Did you expect me to beg? To cry? To plead? For what.
A servant of the Dark Lady would never disavow her. Perhaps I named you false.
I've come to find the source of Ketheric's invulnerability - and end it.
Go on, then. Lay a hand upon my shoulder, and I shall be free.
Was it everything you hoped for? Was it sweet, Sharran, to murder a paladin of Sel√ªne - her daughter - her sword?

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: This is Nightson'gs first node after the player has killed her in combat, and then she's risen again. She should be a little worse for wear here, having just resurrected. Perhaps glowering at the player, breathing heavily for the first node or so.
EditorData.InternalNodeContext: The player 'killed' Nightsong. She has stood up again, immortal.
EditorData.NodeContext: Bitter sarcasm in her voice. She thinks the player is the lowest of the low - a violent idiot. Obviously injured, breathing heavily.
EditorData.VFXTags: some blood stains remaining from her previous "death"

Text.Value: That's all? No abjurations or charms to unweave? All you need is a hand?
Why do you call me Sharran?
There is no moon in this black sky, Sharran - no. There is only your mistress - the void of her. The shadow.
My kin are strong of arm and heart. The necromancer was neither.
Who are you?
HAH! Are you afraid, Sharran? Do you rattle and jump at the realisation that an immortal has your face emblazoned in her mind forevermore?

EditorData.NodeContext: Does not believe the player is here to help her. Huge, bitter laugh on the 'HAH!' Head thrown back, perhaps.

Text.Value: When you have exhausted yourself with foolishness, you will release me. Go on: see.
I have felt you coming. The first in a century.

EditorData.AnimationTags: [REUSE] NS: Pacing back and forth in a LOOP
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: She paces the narrow cage where she's kept, like a tiger. She looks down as she paces, not yet deigning to make eye contact.

Text.Value: I'm not afraid of you - now or ever.
Didn't you, when you murdered me? Perhaps you were stricken blind by foolish devotion.
Forgive me. I should not have harmed you.
You say you're immortal. How is that so?
Those are words I've never heard - not since I've been in this dark dungeon.

EditorData.NodeContext: Softens

Text.Value: I will be freed from these shackles. Ketheric will be made mortal. And then? Lo! Then, I will run him through until he's dead.
Attack.
But if you are a friend - you can be my salvation.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Nightsong kneels, and the player lays a hand on Nightsong's shoulder
EditorData.NodeContext: She is soon to be released. She is grateful, glad.

EditorData.VFXTags: the player lays a hand on Nightsong's shoulder to release her from her prison

Text.Value: Ketheric trapped you here. Why?
You, who have come to drive a dagger through my heart.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: She continues pacing, watching her feet, but slams her open palm against her heart.

Text.Value: How long have you been trapped here?
Do not play games with me, Sharran. You have come to earn your title; to become what your queen has promised. One of her chosen murderers.
Not so fast. What's to stop you from turning on me once you're free?
I am familiar with the Lady of Loss - but I serve a more competent deity. I'm no Sharran.
I serve a more... partisan god than the Dark Lady. I am no Sharran.
I spit on the Dark Lady's name. I serve the Moonmaiden.
I serve a god who walks the light. I am no Sharran.
The Spear of Night. You are not the Nightsinger's chosen champion - her weapon is useless in your hands.
One day, when he is severed from me, Ketheric will die. I will not. And when I am freed, I will remember whose recompense to claim.
Ketheric has sent me to retrieve you.
To kill an immortal: what perfect irony. I think I will.
A bloodsporter, then. No Sharran, but a killer without cause. Fie! What sickness plagues Faer√ªn.
I do not serve Ketheric. I've come to make him vulnerable.

Synopsis: The player encounter Nightsong, an angelic Aasimar and daughter of Selune who has been trapped in the Shadowfell for a century, first to serve as fodder for Dark Justiciars to kill (they must kill a Selunite to ascend), and then to provide Ketheric with immortality through a soul cage. The player can meet her either alone or with Balthazar. Nightsong is defiant and full of rage. She is immortal, so her current trials are, for her, an annoyance, an indignity, but she knows she will ultimately have her revenge. She regards the player with haughty defiance until she is convinced the player is on her side. If she's freed, she'll have 2 big cinematics of becoming free and cleansed by Selune.
